{"variables": [], "instructions": [], "planning": "- Overview\n  This functional block is named `ENERGY` and is used to convert three input energy units (joules `J`, calories `C`, and watt-hours `Wh`) into corresponding output values. Specifically, it standardizes the input energy values by converting them to joules `YJ`, then further converts them to calories `YC` and watt-hours `YWh`.\n\n- Variable Definitions\n  The code defines the following types of variables:\n  - Input variables:\n    - `J`: Input value in joules.\n    - `C`: Input value in calories.\n    - `Wh`: Input value in watt-hours.\n  - Output variables:\n    - `YJ`: Output value in joules.\n    - `YC`: Output value in calories.\n    - `YWh`: Output value in watt-hours.\n\n- Main Logic Section\n  -- REGION Energy Conversion Logic:\n    1. **Calculate Total Joules `YJ`**:\n       Convert the input watt-hours `Wh` to joules (1 watt-hour = 3600 joules), convert the input calories `C` to joules (1 calorie ≈ 4.1868 joules), then sum them with the input joules `J` to obtain the total joules `YJ`.\n       Formula: `YJ := J + Wh * 3600.0 + C * 4.1868;`\n\n    2. **Calculate Calories `YC`**:\n       Convert the total joules `YJ` to calories (1 joule ≈ 0.238845896627496 calories).\n       Formula: `YC := YJ * 0.238845896627496;`\n\n    3. **Calculate Watt-Hours `YWh`**:\n       Convert the total joules `YJ` to watt-hours (1 joule ≈ 2.7777777778E-004 watt-hours).\n       Formula: `YWh := YJ * 2.7777777778E-004;`\n\n  The entire logic performs straightforward mathematical operations to convert the input energy values into standardized output units, facilitating subsequent use or display.", "name": "ENERGY"}